Capstone Project: Create a Customer Segmentation Report for Arvato Financial Services¶

In this project, you will analyze demographics data for customers of a mail-order sales company in Germany, comparing it against demographics information for the general population. You'll use unsupervised learning techniques to perform customer segmentation, identifying the parts of the population that best describe the core customer base of the company. Then, you'll apply what you've learned on a third dataset with demographics information for targets of a marketing campaign for the company, and use a model to predict which individuals are most likely to convert into becoming customers for the company. The data that you will use has been provided by our partners at Bertelsmann Arvato Analytics, and represents a real-life data science task.

If you completed the first term of this program, you will be familiar with the first part of this project, from the unsupervised learning project. The versions of those two datasets used in this project will include many more features and has not been pre-cleaned. You are also free to choose whatever approach you'd like to analyzing the data rather than follow pre-determined steps. In your work on this project, make sure that you carefully document your steps and decisions, since your main deliverable for this project will be a blog post reporting your findings.

Part 1: Get to Know the Data¶

There are four data files associated with this project:

  • Udacity_AZDIAS_052018.csv: Demographics data for the general population of Germany; 891 211 persons (rows) x 366 features (columns).
  • Udacity_CUSTOMERS_052018.csv: Demographics data for customers of a mail-order company; 191 652 persons (rows) x 369 features (columns).
  • Udacity_MAILOUT_052018_TRAIN.csv: Demographics data for individuals who were targets of a marketing campaign; 42 982 persons (rows) x 367 (columns).
  • Udacity_MAILOUT_052018_TEST.csv: Demographics data for individuals who were targets of a marketing campaign; 42 833 persons (rows) x 366 (columns).

Each row of the demographics files represents a single person, but also includes information outside of individuals, including information about their household, building, and neighborhood. Use the information from the first two files to figure out how customers ("CUSTOMERS") are similar to or differ from the general population at large ("AZDIAS"), then use your analysis to make predictions on the other two files ("MAILOUT"), predicting which recipients are most likely to become a customer for the mail-order company.

The "CUSTOMERS" file contains three extra columns ('CUSTOMER_GROUP', 'ONLINE_PURCHASE', and 'PRODUCT_GROUP'), which provide broad information about the customers depicted in the file. The original "MAILOUT" file included one additional column, "RESPONSE", which indicated whether or not each recipient became a customer of the company. For the "TRAIN" subset, this column has been retained, but in the "TEST" subset it has been removed; it is against that withheld column that your final predictions will be assessed in the Kaggle competition.

Otherwise, all of the remaining columns are the same between the three data files. For more information about the columns depicted in the files, you can refer to two Excel spreadsheets provided in the workspace. One of them is a top-level list of attributes and descriptions, organized by informational category. The other is a detailed mapping of data values for each feature in alphabetical order.

In the below cell, we've provided some initial code to load in the first two datasets. Note for all of the .csv data files in this project that they're semicolon (;) delimited, so an additional argument in the read_csv() call has been included to read in the data properly. Also, considering the size of the datasets, it may take some time for them to load completely.

You'll notice when the data is loaded in that a warning message will immediately pop up. Before you really start digging into the modeling and analysis, you're going to need to perform some cleaning. Take some time to browse the structure of the data and look over the informational spreadsheets to understand the data values. Make some decisions on which features to keep, which features to drop, and if any revisions need to be made on data formats. It'll be a good idea to create a function with pre-processing steps, since you'll need to clean all of the datasets before you work with them.

1.2 Handle unknown values and analzye missing data¶

The dataset of the general population consists of 891221 entries (=rows) and 366 features (=columns). In total around 10% of the entries are missing, however, there are still unknown entries in the dataset. To identify the codes for unknown entries, the supporting description files were manually scanned, and missing values and undescribed features were documented in a new table: feature_info.csv.

# functions to separate rows into complete and incomplete datasets
def separate_rows_missing(data, missing_threshold=0):
    """
    Separate data into a complete and an incomplete dataset based on the missing_threshold of missing values
    in each row.
    
    Inputs
    ------
    data : dataframe
        data to be split
        
    missing_threshold : int (optional)
        number of missing values on which the data is split into complete (<=) and incomplete (>)
        
    Outputs
    -------
    complete_rows : dataframe
        dataset with less or equal than missing_threshold values
        
    incomplete_rows : dataframe
        dataset with more than missing_threshold values
    """
    # get total number of rows
    n_entries = data.shape[0]
    
    # get number of missing values per row
    missing_in_row = data.isnull().sum(axis=1)
    
    # split dataset
    complete_rows = data.loc[missing_in_row <= missing_threshold]
    incomplete_rows = data.loc[missing_in_row > missing_threshold]

    print('# complete row fraction:   {:.1f}%'.format(complete_rows.shape[0]/n_entries*100.0))
    print('# incomplete row fraction: {:.1f}%'.format(incomplete_rows.shape[0]/n_entries*100.0))
    
    return (complete_rows, incomplete_rows)


# function to plot distributions from complete and incomplete dataset
def plot_feature_distributions(column, complete_data, incomplete_data, plottitle=''):
    """
    Plot distribution of feature (=column) in complete_data and incompelete_data in a single barplot.
    
    Inputs
    ------
    column : str
        feature name
        
    complete_data : dataframe
        dataset with less or equal than missing_threshold values
        
    incomplete_data : dataframe
        dataset with more than missing_threshold values
    
    Outputs
    -------
    """
        
    # get number of rows
    n_complete = complete_data.shape[0]
    n_incomplete = incomplete_data.shape[0]
    n_total = n_complete + n_incomplete
    
    # calculate proportions
    complete_props = complete_data[column].value_counts(normalize=True, sort=False)
    incomplete_props = incomplete_data[column].value_counts(normalize=True)
    
    # combine into dataframe for plotting
    df_complete = pd.DataFrame(complete_props).reset_index()
    df_complete.columns = ['VALUE', 'PROPORTION']
    df_complete['DATASET'] = 'complete'
    
    df_incomplete = pd.DataFrame(incomplete_props).reset_index()
    df_incomplete.columns = ['VALUE', 'PROPORTION']
    df_incomplete['DATASET'] = 'incomplete'

    df = pd.concat([df_complete, df_incomplete], axis=0)
    
    # plot proportions in one barplot
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    sns.barplot(data=df, x='VALUE', y='PROPORTION', hue='DATASET')
    plt.title(column + ": <=" + plottitle + " missing values")
    plt.tight_layout()
    
    return plt.gca()

1.6 Impute missing values¶

As up to 9 missing values per row were allowed to use 78% of the data, the missing values need to be imputed. As most features are categorical or ordinal features, and as the numerical features have highly skewed distributions, missing data will be imputed using the median value of each feature.

In [43]:
# check number of missing values before imputation
azdias_features.isna().sum().sum()

1270545
In [44]:

1.8 Summarize data wrangling in cleaning function¶

In [50]:
# cleaning function to prepare data
def clean_data(df, missing_values, remove_lines=True, lines_threshold=9, impute=True):
    """
    Perform feature trimming, re-encoding, and engineering for demographics
    data
    
    INPUT: Demographics DataFrame
    OUTPUT: Trimmed and cleaned demographics DataFrame
    """
    # create copy of dataframe
    df_cleaned = df.copy()
    
    # 1. replace missing and unknown values by NaN, and remove columns and lines with many missing values
    
    # loop over columns and replace missing/unknown data skipping columns without missing/unknown codes
    for i, col in enumerate(df_cleaned.columns):
        if missing_values[i] != []:
            df_cleaned[col] = df[col].replace(missing_values[i], np.NaN)
            
    # drop columns with many missing values and with non-related information (e.g. number of entry)
    drop_columns_missing = ['ALTER_KIND4', 'TITEL_KZ', 'ALTER_KIND3', 'ALTER_KIND2', 'ALTER_KIND1', 'VHA',
                            'AGER_TYP', 'EXTSEL992', 'KK_KUNDENTYP', 'KBA05_BAUMAX', 'VERDICHTUNGSRAUM',
                            'D19_LETZTER_KAUF_BRANCHE', 'GEBURTSJAHR', 'ALTER_HH', 'ALTERSKATEGORIE_FEIN',
                            'LNR', 'EINGEFUEGT_AM', 'GEMEINDETYP', 'HH_DELTA_FLAG', 'VHN']

    df_cleaned.drop(drop_columns_missing, axis=1, inplace=True)    
    
    # drop rows with more than 9 missing values
    if remove_lines == True:
        df_cleaned, _ = separate_rows_missing(df_cleaned, missing_threshold=lines_threshold)
    
    # drop unexplained or unconsistent categorical features
    drop_categorical_features = ['AKT_DAT_KL', 'FINANZTYP', 'CAMEO_DEUG_2015', 'CAMEO_DEU_2015',
                                 'D19_KONSUMTYP_MAX', 'GEBAEUDETYP', 'LP_FAMILIE_FEIN', 'LP_FAMILIE_GROB',
                                 'LP_LEBENSPHASE_FEIN', 'NATIONALITAET_KZ']

    df_cleaned.drop(drop_categorical_features, axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    # 2. re-encoding features
    
    # re-encoding OST_WEST_KZ from string to binary (W=0, O=1) inplace
    df_cleaned.replace({'OST_WEST_KZ': {'W': 0, 'O': 1}}, inplace=True)
    
    # re-encoding VERS_TYP to binary feature
    df_cleaned.replace({'VERS_TYP': {1.0: 0}}, inplace=True)
    df_cleaned.replace({'VERS_TYP': {2.0: 1}}, inplace=True)
    
    # re-encoding categorical features
    # CAMEO_INTL_2015
    df_encoded = pd.DataFrame(index=df_cleaned.index)
    df_encoded['CAMEO_INTL_2015'] = df_cleaned['CAMEO_INTL_2015']
    df_encoded['FAMILY_WEALTH'] = df_cleaned['CAMEO_INTL_2015'].apply(lambda x: int(str(x)[0]) if pd.notna(x) else x)
    df_encoded['FAMILY_TYPE'] = df_cleaned['CAMEO_INTL_2015'].apply(lambda x: int(str(x)[1]) if pd.notna(x) else x)
    
    # PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE
    df_encoded['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'] = df_cleaned['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'].astype(str)

    replace_decades = {'1.0': 1940, '2.0': 1940, '3.0': 1950, '4.0': 1950, '5.0': 1960, '6.0': 1960, '7.0': 1960,
                       '8.0': 1970, '9.0': 1970, '10.0': 1980, '11.0': 1980, '12.0': 1980, '13.0': 1980,
                       '14.0': 1990, '15.0': 1990}

    replace_avantgarde = {'1.0': 0, '2.0': 1, '3.0': 0, '4.0': 1, '5.0': 0, '6.0': 1, '7.0': 1,
                          '8.0': 0, '9.0': 1, '10.0': 0, '11.0': 1, '12.0': 0, '13.0': 1,
                          '14.0': 0, '15.0': 1}

    # replace values and add to the dataframe of encoded variables
    df_encoded['YOUTH_DECADE'] = df_encoded.replace({'PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE': replace_decades})['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE']
    df_encoded['MAIN_AVANT'] = df_encoded.replace({'PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE': replace_avantgarde})['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE']
    
    # drop original columns from dataframe of encoded and original features and join new features to dataframe
    df_encoded.drop(['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE', 'CAMEO_INTL_2015'], axis=1, inplace=True)
    df_cleaned.drop(['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE', 'CAMEO_INTL_2015'], axis=1, inplace=True)
    df_cleaned = df_cleaned.join(df_encoded)
    
    # convert all values to float
    df_cleaned = df_cleaned.astype(float)
    
    # drop columns that are strongly correlated to other features
    drop_corr_columns = ['ANZ_STATISTISCHE_HAUSHALTE', 'CJT_TYP_1', 'CJT_TYP_2', 'CJT_TYP_3', 'CJT_TYP_4',
                         'CJT_TYP_5', 'CJT_TYP_6', 'D19_BANKEN_ANZ_12', 'D19_BANKEN_DATUM',
                         'D19_BANKEN_ONLINE_DATUM', 'D19_GESAMT_ANZ_12', 'D19_GESAMT_DATUM',

# implement function to plot explained variance from PCA
def plot_pca(pca, limit=20):
    
    n_PC = len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
    idx_PC = range(1, n_PC+1)
    var_PC = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
    cum_var_PC = np.cumsum(var_PC)
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
    plt.bar(idx_PC[:limit], var_PC[:limit], linewidth=0.0)
    plt.xticks(range(1,limit+1))
    plt.ylim(0.0, np.around(np.max(var_PC), decimals=1))
    for i in range(0, limit):
        plt.annotate('%.1f%%' % (100.0*var_PC[i]), (i+1, var_PC[i]+0.005), ha='center',
                     rotation=90.0, weight='bold', color=tableau10[0])
    plt.xlabel('principal component')
    plt.ylabel('explained variance')
    
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
    plt.plot(idx_PC, cum_var_PC, '.--', color=tableau10[1])
    plt.hlines([0.5, 0.66, 0.8, 0.9], xmin=1, xmax=n_PC, linestyles='--')
    plt.ylim(ymin=0.0)
    plt.xlabel('number of principal components')
    plt.ylabel('cumulated explained variance')
    plt.annotate('50%', (1, 0.52), weight='bold', color=tableau10[1])
    plt.annotate('66%', (1, 0.68), weight='bold', color=tableau10[1])
    plt.annotate('80%', (1, 0.82), weight='bold', color=tableau10[1])
    plt.annotate('90%', (1, 0.92), weight='bold', color=tableau10[1])

    fig.tight_layout()
    fig.savefig('plots/PCA.png', dpi=300.0)

Observations

  • 21% of the variance are explained by the first 5 PCs
  • with 40 PCs, at least 50% of the variance can be captured
  • with 140 PCs, at least 80% of the variance can be captured
  • to capture 90% of the variance in the data, 190 PCs are required
  • decision: use 10 PCs for the clustering analysis to avoid PCs with explained variance equal or below 1% and a too fine-grained feature space.

# implement function to analyze and plot feature weights in PC
def plot_pca_weights(df, component, threshold=0.1):
    
    # extract explained variance and weights
    explained_variance = float(df.iloc[component-1, -1])
    weights = df.iloc[component-1, 0:-1].values
    features = np.array((df.columns[0:-1]))

    # sort values and features by weight
    idx = np.argsort(-1.0*weights)
    weights_sorted = weights[idx]
    features_sorted = features[idx]

    
    # reduce to features with weights higher +-0.1
    weights_pos = np.trim_zeros(np.where(weights_sorted >= threshold, weights_sorted, 0.0))
    weights_neg = np.trim_zeros(np.where(weights_sorted <= -1.0*threshold, weights_sorted, 0.0))
    weights_main = np.hstack((weights_pos, weights_neg))

    n_pos = len(weights_pos)
    n_neg = len(weights_neg)
    n_main = n_pos + n_neg

    features_main = np.hstack((features_sorted[0:n_pos], features_sorted[-n_neg:]))
    feature_idx = range(1,n_main+1)
    
    
    # plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
    ax = plt.gca()
    plt.bar(feature_idx, weights_main, align='center', linewidth=0.0)
    plt.xticks(feature_idx)
    ax.set_xticklabels([])
    for i in range(n_pos):
        plt.annotate('%s' % features_main[i], (i+1, -0.01), rotation=90, ha='center', va='top', weight='bold')
        plt.annotate('%.1f%%' % (weights_main[i]*100.0), (i+1, weights_main[i]+0.01),
                     rotation=90, ha='center', va='bottom', weight='bold')
    
    for i in range(n_neg):
        plt.annotate('%s' % features_main[n_pos+i], (n_pos+i+1, 0.01), rotation=90, ha='center', va='bottom', weight='bold')
        plt.annotate('%.1f%%' % (weights_main[n_pos+i]*100.0), (n_pos+i+1, weights_main[n_pos+i]-0.01),
                     rotation=90, ha='center', va='top', weight='bold')
    
    plt.ylim(ymin=np.around(np.min(weights_main), 1)-0.1, ymax=np.around(np.max(weights_main), 1)+0.1)
    plt.title('principal component %i | %.1f%% explained variance | weights larger 10%% shown' % (component, explained_variance*100.0),
              weight='bold', fontsize='large')

Part 3: Supervised Learning Model¶

Now that you've found which parts of the population are more likely to be customers of the mail-order company, it's time to build a prediction model. Each of the rows in the "MAILOUT" data files represents an individual that was targeted for a mailout campaign. Ideally, we should be able to use the demographic information from each individual to decide whether or not it will be worth it to include that person in the campaign.

The "MAILOUT" data has been split into two approximately equal parts, each with almost 43 000 data rows. In this part, you can verify your model with the "TRAIN" partition, which includes a column, "RESPONSE", that states whether or not a person became a customer of the company following the campaign. In the next part, you'll need to create predictions on the "TEST" partition, where the "RESPONSE" column has been withheld.

3.2 Algorithm screening¶

In [122]:
def screen_classifier(clf, cv, X, y, train_sizes, scoring='roc_auc', clf_name='', plot=True):
    """
    Create learning curve for a given classifier.
    
    INPUTS
    ------
    clf
        classifier
    cv
        cross-validator
        
    X : ndarray
        feature data
        
    y : ndarryy
        labels
        
    train_sizes : list
        fractions of training set to be used
    
    scoring : str
        scoring metric
    
    plot : boolean
        switch to enable plot of learning curve
        
    OUTPUTS
    -------
    final_score_mean : float
        mean final validation score using complete training set
        
    final_score_std : float
        std final validation score using complete training set        
    """

    # calculate learing curve
    scores = learning_curve(clf_pipe, X, y, cv=cv, scoring=scoring,
                        train_sizes=train_sizes, shuffle=True, random_state=10, n_jobs=-1, verbose=1)

    # assign training sizes and training and validation scores
    train_sizes, train_scores, validation_scores = scores
    
    # calculate mean and std of scores
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    validation_scores_mean = np.mean(validation_scores, axis=1)
    validation_scores_std = np.std(validation_scores, axis=1)
    
    final_score_mean = validation_scores_mean[-1]
    final_score_std = validation_scores_std[-1]
    
    # report scores
    print(clf_name + ': ROC-AUC score = {:.4f} ({:.4f})'.format(final_score_mean, final_score_std))
        
    # plot learning curve
    if plot == True:
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
        plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o--', label='training')
        plt.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean-train_scores_std, train_scores_mean+train_scores_std,
                         alpha=0.15)
        plt.plot(train_sizes, validation_scores_mean, 'o--', label='validation')
        plt.fill_between(train_sizes, validation_scores_mean-train_scores_std, validation_scores_mean+train_scores_std,
                         alpha=0.15)
        plt.ylim(0.45, 1.05)
        plt.xlabel('training samples')
        plt.ylabel('ROC-AUC score')
        plt.legend(loc=0)
        plt.title(clf_name + ' (ROC-AUC = {:.4f}+-{:.4f})'.format(final_score_mean, final_score_std))
        fig.tight_layout()
        
    return (final_score_mean, final_score_std)

3.3 Improve predictions: reduce feature space¶

Another option to improve the model performance is to reduce the feature space. Therefore, two options are explored:

  1. use features with high/low weights to principal component 1;
    • the previous cluster anaylsis showed that all cluster that are overrepresented in the customer dataset have high PC1 values, while all underrepresented clusters had low values of PC1
  2. a Random Forest classifier is used to select the most relevant features

3.3.1 Use features from principal component 1¶

In [130]:
# implement function to get most relevant features from principal components
def get_principal_features(df, components, threshold=0.1):
    
    # initialize lists of features and indices
    features_total = []
    feature_indices_total = []
    
    # loop over principal components
    for component in components:
    
        # extract weights
        weights = df.iloc[component-1, 0:-1].values
        features = np.array((df.columns[0:-1]))

        # sort values and features by weight
        idx = np.argsort(-1.0*weights)
        weights_sorted = weights[idx]
        features_sorted = features[idx]


        # reduce to features with weights higher +-0.1
        weights_pos = np.trim_zeros(np.where(weights_sorted >= threshold, weights_sorted, 0.0))
        weights_neg = np.trim_zeros(np.where(weights_sorted <= -1.0*threshold, weights_sorted, 0.0))
        weights_main = np.hstack((weights_pos, weights_neg))

        # get indices of features above/below threshold
        n_pos = len(weights_pos)
        n_neg = len(weights_neg)

        # build list of principal features
        features_total.extend(np.hstack((features_sorted[0:n_pos], features_sorted[-n_neg:])).tolist())
    
    # remove duplicate features
    features_total = list(set(features_total))                          
                              
    # get indices of all principal features
    for i in range(len(features_total)):
        feature_indices_total.append(df.columns.get_loc(features_total[i]))

    # convert index list to array
    features_idx = np.array(feature_indices_total)

    return (features_total, features_idx)

Part 4: Kaggle Competition¶

Now that you've created a model to predict which individuals are most likely to respond to a mailout campaign, it's time to test that model in competition through Kaggle. If you click on the link here, you'll be taken to the competition page where, if you have a Kaggle account, you can enter. If you're one of the top performers, you may have the chance to be contacted by a hiring manager from Arvato or Bertelsmann for an interview!

Your entry to the competition should be a CSV file with two columns. The first column should be a copy of "LNR", which acts as an ID number for each individual in the "TEST" partition. The second column, "RESPONSE", should be some measure of how likely each individual became a customer this might not be a straightforward probability. As you should have found in Part 2, there is a large output class imbalance, where most individuals did not respond to the mailout. Thus, predicting individual classes and using accuracy does not seem to be an appropriate performance evaluation method. Instead, the competition will be using AUC to evaluate performance. The exact values of the "RESPONSE" column do not matter as much: only that the higher values try to capture as many of the actual customers as possible, early in the ROC curve sweep.
